# /etc/pam.d/tessera-only — CERT-ONLY mode (auth + account only).
#
# Cert is the sole authentication factor: when this snippet is active in a
# PAM service, the password / common-auth chain is BYPASSED entirely on
# successful cert verification, and DIE'd on failure.
#
# How it works:
#   `auth [success=done default=die] pam_tessera.so`
#   - on success → PAM stops walking the auth stack with PAM_SUCCESS;
#                  any later `@include common-auth` is skipped.
#   - on failure → PAM stops with PAM_AUTH_ERR; later modules are skipped
#                  too, so password is never offered as a fallback.
#
# Inclusion order matters: this snippet MUST appear BEFORE any
# `@include common-auth` / `auth required pam_unix.so` line in the host
# PAM config; integrate-pam.sh handles that placement automatically.
#
# NOTE (0.3.12+): the `session` phase intentionally lives OUTSIDE this
# snippet. `pam_sm_open_session` of Tessera needs `XDG_SESSION_ID`
# pushed into the PAM environment by `pam_systemd.so` (delivered via
# `@include common-session` on Debian/Astra), and `common-session`
# almost always sits at the bottom of the host PAM file — i.e. AFTER
# wherever this snippet ends up included in the auth/account block.
# `integrate-pam.sh` therefore inserts an explicit
# `session required pam_tessera.so` line AFTER `@include common-session`
# instead of bundling it here. If you wire this snippet in by hand,
# remember to add that session line yourself.
#
# WARNING: lost or blocked USB token = total lockout. See
# docs/operations.md § 3.6 for the pre-deploy checklist.

auth     [success=done default=die]  pam_tessera.so
account  required                    pam_tessera.so
